Provinces will hold some level of endemism, principally at the level of species. The dominant biogeographic forcing agents defining an ecoregion vary from location to location but may include isolation, upwelling, nutrient inputs, freshwater influx, temperature regimes, ice regimes, exposure, sediments, currents and bathymetric or coastal complexity.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: This system is defined using the definition from Boyde et al. (1992) and Darymple et al. (1992). An estuary is the area headward of the seaward limit of a drowned river valley which receives sediment input from both river and marine sources and contains geomorphic and sedimentary facies influenced by tide, wave and river processes. All estuaries ideally possess a three-fold (tripartite) structure: an outer, marine-dominated portion where the net bedload transport is headward; a relatively low-energy central zone where there is net bedload convergence; and an inner, river-dominated (but marine-influenced) part where the net transport is seaward. These three zones are not equally developed in all estuaries because of factors such as sediment availability, coastal zone gradient and the stage of estuary evolution.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: The Marine System is defined by salinity, which is typically 35 ‰, although can measure as low as 0.5 ‰ during the period of average annual low flow near freshwater outflows. This system has little or no significant dilution from fresh water except near the mouths of estuaries and rivers. The Marine System includes all non-estuarine waters from the coastline to central oceans. The landward boundary of this system is either the linear boundary across the mouth of an estuary or the limit of the intertidal zone.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: The Nearshore System extends from the upper limit of the intertidal zone (Highest Astronomical Tide - HAT) to the 30 m depth contour (as chart datum). As stated in the CMEC Standard (FGDC 2012), the 30 m depth contour was selected as a useful cut-off between shallower nearshore and deeper offshore waters. It is intended to represent an ecologically significant depth to which water column and benthic processes are strongly coupled. Surface currents and waves impinge the bottom at the storm wave base (Keen and Holland 2010) and vertical circulation generally distributes nutrients and sediments throughout the water column. The photic zone extends through the entire water column except in extreme cases (Kleypas et al. 1999). The presence of nutrients and light support the growth of vegetation on the seafloor including seagrass and macroalgal beds, and 30 meters generally represents the depth to which most living coral is found.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An IMCRA provincial bioregion reflects biogeographic patterns in distributions of bottom-dwelling fish. Provincial bioregions were defined for the continental shelf for IMCRA v3.3, and for the continental slope for the National Marine Bioregionalisation using similar analytical techniques. In both cases the distributions of demersal (bottom-dwelling) fish were plotted onto a line divided into equally spaced sections. The number of species in each section and the similarity between sections were calculated using a statistical tool called the Jaccard Index. Where the Jaccard Index changed greatly between sections a boundary was defined indicating differences in species assemblages between regions. Two types of provincial bioregions are defined in the IMCRA benthic bioregionalisation: provinces, which represent regions of biotic endemism; and transitions, which generally occur between the provinces, and are less well-defined mixing areas that capture the overlap of demersal fish species ranges between the provinces.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An IMCRA provincial bioregion reflects biogeographic patterns in distributions of bottom-dwelling fish. Provincial bioregions were defined for the continental shelf for IMCRA v3.3, and for the continental slope for the National Marine Bioregionalisation using similar analytical techniques. In both cases the distributions of demersal (bottom-dwelling) fish were plotted onto a line divided into equally spaced sections. The number of species in each section and the similarity between sections were calculated using a statistical tool called the Jaccard Index. Where the Jaccard Index changed greatly between sections a boundary was defined indicating differences in species assemblages between regions. Two types of provincial bioregions are defined in the IMCRA benthic bioregionalisation: provinces, which represent regions of biotic endemism; and transitions, which generally occur between the provinces, and are less well-defined mixing areas that capture the overlap of demersal fish species ranges between the provinces.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An IMCRA provincial bioregion reflects biogeographic patterns in distributions of bottom-dwelling fish. Provincial bioregions were defined for the continental shelf for IMCRA v3.3, and for the continental slope for the National Marine Bioregionalisation using similar analytical techniques. In both cases the distributions of demersal (bottom-dwelling) fish were plotted onto a line divided into equally spaced sections. The number of species in each section and the similarity between sections were calculated using a statistical tool called the Jaccard Index. Where the Jaccard Index changed greatly between sections a boundary was defined indicating differences in species assemblages between regions. Two types of provincial bioregions are defined in the IMCRA benthic bioregionalisation: provinces, which represent regions of biotic endemism; and transitions, which generally occur between the provinces, and are less well-defined mixing areas that capture the overlap of demersal fish species ranges between the provinces.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: The Seamap classification for substrate is based on the CMECS (FGDC, 2012) Substratum component, but with the modification of introducing a level describing the hardness of the substratum, which replaces the CMECS 'Origin' classifier. This modification is the same as is described in Edmunds and Flynn (2015). The Substratum Component of the CMECS is useful because it defines unique classes based on specific grainsizes or compositions, and the lower levels can be collapsed into higher level groups as required by the resolution of mapping. However, using standard CMECS, it is not possible to collapse the lower levels into hard and soft categories, and this represented a disadvantage of the scheme. The distinction between hard and soft substrata is one of the simplest and most common distinctions made when mapping the seafloor, and can be determined in all methods used for habitat mapping, including the use of satellite imagery, aerial photography, acoustic surveys and underwater video/photography. In terms of ecology, this characteristic also represents an important division between substratum types that are able to support reef ecosystems (hard), and those that cannot (soft). For these reasons a node describing the hardness of the substratum was included as indicated earlier. This modification is the same as that proposed in Edmunds and Flynn (2015). Hardness refers to the physical properties of the substratum, and can be determined through knowledge of acoustic or optical reflectivity, as well as by the stability of the substratum. This means that habitats such as worm or shell reefs and rhodolith beds are all classified as hard substratum, despite not being hard in the literal sense, whilst pebble habitats are not considered hard because they are not sufficiently stable to support a reef ecosystem.

A habitat where the dominance of a single biotic class (Vegetation, Microbes, Invertebrates or Urchin Barrens) is unclear, or where the composition/biomass/surface coverage of the second-most dominant class lies within 30 % margin of the most-dominant biotic class.

An area where the absence of fleshy seaweeds on hard substratum is attributed to over-grazing from sea urchins. These areas are largely devoid of fleshy macroalgal cover where seaweeds would otherwise be expected to occur, and sea urchins are typically present at high densities, although once formed an urchin barren can be maintained by relatively low densities of urchins.

A habitat where the dominance of a single Vegetation subclass (Wetland Vegetation, Macrophytes) cannot be identified, or where the composition/biomass/surface coverage of the second-most dominant subclass lies within 30 % margin of the most-dominant subclass.

A habitat where the dominance of a single Wetland Vegetation group (Mangroves, Saltmarsh) cannot be identified, or where the composition/biomass/surface coverage of the second-most dominant group lies within 30 % margin of the most-dominant group.

A habitat where the dominance of a Macrophyte group (Macroalgae, Seagrass) cannot be identified, or where the composition/biomass/surface coverage of the second-most dominant group lies within 30 % margin of the most-dominant group.

A habitat where the dominance of a single microbial subclass (Stromatolites, Bacterial Mat, Microphytobenthos) cannot be identified, or where the composition/biomass/surface coverage of the second-most dominant subclass lies within 30 % margin of the most-dominant subclass.

A habitat where the dominance of a single Invertebrate subclass (Non-molluscan Filter Feeders, Bioturbators, Shelled Biota) cannot be identified, or where the composition/biomass/surface coverage of the second-most dominant subclass lies within 30 % margin of the most-dominant subclass.

A habitat where the dominance of a single Non-molluscan Filter Feeder group (Non-coral Cnidaria, Corals, Worms, Bryozoans, Sponges, Ascidians) cannot be identified, or where the composition/biomass/surface coverage of the second-most dominant group lies within 30 % margin of the most-dominant group.

A habitat where the dominance of a single Shelled Biota group (Oyster, Mussel, Screwshell, Other) cannot be identified, or where the composition/biomass/surface coverage of the second-most dominant group lies within 30 % margin of the most-dominant group.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An IMCRA provincial bioregion reflects biogeographic patterns in distributions of bottom-dwelling fish. Provincial bioregions were defined for the continental shelf for IMCRA v3.3, and for the continental slope for the National Marine Bioregionalisation using similar analytical techniques. In both cases the distributions of demersal (bottom-dwelling) fish were plotted onto a line divided into equally spaced sections. The number of species in each section and the similarity between sections were calculated using a statistical tool called the Jaccard Index. Where the Jaccard Index changed greatly between sections a boundary was defined indicating differences in species assemblages between regions. Two types of provincial bioregions are defined in the IMCRA benthic bioregionalisation: provinces, which represent regions of biotic endemism; and transitions, which generally occur between the provinces, and are less well-defined mixing areas that capture the overlap of demersal fish species ranges between the provinces.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: The CMECS (FGDC, 2012) 'origin' classifier provides valuable information on the source of substrate (geologic, biogenic and anthropogenic); however, it can also be one of the more difficult characteristics to classify as identified by Edmunds and Flynn (2015). The resolution required to clearly identify the origin of a substratum depends on the substratum in question. For example, rhodolith beds can be identified from acoustic surveys with simple in situ observation e.g. camera drop, whereas determining whether a sand is dominated by a mineral composition or Halimeda sp. may require analysis of sediment samples. CMECS includes 'origin' at the highest level of the substratum component hierarchy, which makes subsequent classification of substrata difficult if the 'origin' is unknown. Generally, 'origin' might be something identified at finer (lower) levels in a substrate because one would need to be at this level of resolution to obtain the information. Seamap has therefore included the origin classifier in the Seamap scheme, but has included it as a 'floating' category (rather than anchoring it within the substratum category).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A wave-dominated estuary typically possess a well-defined tripartite zonation: a marine sand body comprised of barrier, washover, tidal inlet and tidal delta deposits; a fine-grained (generally muddy) central basin; and a bay-head delta that experiences tidal and/or salt-water influence. Wave dominated estuaries are often referred to as ‘coastal lakes’ or ‘lagoons’.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) – UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: This zone extends from LAT (Lowest Astronomical Tide) to Highest Astronomical Tide (HAT), i.e. areas where the substratum is regularly or periodically exposed and flooded by tides.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) – UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: This zone cover areas below LAT (Lowest Astronomical Tide), i.e. areas where the substratum is continuously submerged.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) – UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: All areas periodically or episodically exposed to air; intertidal.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) – UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Subtidal areas where the benthos are algal dominated, wave-disturbed or within the euphotic zone

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) – UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Subtidal areas where the benthos are below the euphotic zone and light penetration is thus insufficient to allow algae to dominate. May experience some wave action, and tidal currents may exert a strong influence. These zones are typically characterised by animal communities, although very sparse algae may be present.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) – UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A tide-dominated estuary consists of elongate sand bars and broad sand flats that pass headward into low-sinuosity channels; net sand transport is headward in these areas. The equivalent of the central basin consists of a zone of tight meanders where bedload transport by flood-tidal and river currents is equal in the long term, while the inner, river-dominated zone has a single, low-sinuosity (straight) channel.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Where the substratum is composed of a greater percentage of geologic materials than either biogenic or anthropogenic. Geologic substrata can be igneous, metamorphic or sedimentary particles of any grain size class.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) – UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Any estuary not defined as either wave- or tide-dominated.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Substratum that has a greater percentage cover, weight or composition of anthropogenic material than of either geologic or biogenic material. Anthropogenic material can be anything that is man-made, or which has been intentionally or accidentally placed by humans.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) – UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An area where an assessment was made. however a classification was not possible (e.g. due to inadequate resolution, or poor quality or ambiguous data).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Biogenic substrata that are dominated by partially or fully cemented calcareous or muddy/sandy tubes of polychaetes or other worm-like fauna.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A biogenic substratum that is dominated by non-living crustose and calcareous algae. Living algae may be present, but these are described under the Biotic Component.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An area where mapping has occurred, but where substratum characteristics were not assessed. An NA classification is distinct from an Unknown classification in that an Unknown implies an assessment was made however a classification was not possible (e.g. due to inadequate resolution, or poor quality data).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A biogenic substratum that is composed of sediments from a terrigenous origin, e.g. soils and other organic materials eroded from the land.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A deep-sea substratum that is composed of > 30 % tests, shells or frustules of small plankton.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A geologic substratum that is composed of  ≥ 60 % metamorphic rock.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A geologic substratum that is composed of  ≥ 60 % igneous rock.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A geologic substratum that is composed of  ≥ 60 % sedimentary rock.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An anthropogenic substratum that is dominated (≥ 60 %) by natural mineral materials. This includes breakwaters and artificial reefs made of natural stone. If the origin cannot be identified, it is assumed to be natural and classed under Geologic Origin.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An anthropogenic substratum that is dominated by wood and woody materials that were constructed and deposited in the marine environment by humans.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An anthropogenic substratum that is composed of unnatural mineral materials used in construction that have been assembled and deposited by humans, e.g. concrete, plastic, fibreglass, porcelain, rubber.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Substrata of any origin where ≥ 80% of the substratum surface is hard (i.e. acoustically or optically hard and/or stable enough through time to be able to maintain a reef ecosystem of some form).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An anthropogenic substratum that constitutes ≥ 60 % metal that was manufactured by humans.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Worm substrata that comprise tubes composed of calcium carbonate that have been constructed by serpulid worms (e.g. Serpulid sp., Galeolaria caespitose).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Worm substrata that comprise tubes composed of shell and sand fragments that have been constructed by sabellariid worms (e.g. Idanthyrsus pennatus)

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Biogenic substrata that are primarily composed of rhodoliths, a crustose algae that forms rounded calcareous nodules.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Biogenic substrata that are primarily composed of Halimeda sp., a calcareous marine alga that can form extensive algal sands once it has died.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Substrata of any origin where ≥ 80% of the substratum surface is soft (i.e. acoustically or optically soft and/or not stable enough through time to be able to maintain a reef ecosystem of some form). This is equivalent to a substratum where < 20 %  of the substratum surface is hard.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Oozes that are formed primarily from the siliceous tests, shells or frustules of diatoms, radiolarian or other siliceous plankton. These are typically most abundant at depths deeper than the Carbon Compensation Depth ( ~ 4000 m), because unlike carbonate oozes, silica-based oozes will not dissolve in the cooler and slightly more acidic waters at these depths.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Oozes that are formed primarily from the calcareous tests, shells or frustules of foraminifera, cocolithophores, pteropods and other calcareous plankton. These are most abundant in water at depths shallower than the Carbon Compensation Depth (~ 4000 m), because below this depth carbonate is usually dissolved given the colder and slightly more acidic waters.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Siliceous oozes where the composition is dominated by the test and shells of radiolarian.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Siliceous oozes where the composition is dominated by the test and shells of diatoms.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Carbonate oozes dominated by the tests and shells of foraminifera.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Carbonate oozes dominated by the tests and shells of cocolithophores.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Carbonate oozes dominated by the tests and shells of pteropods.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: The Seamap classification of biota is a modification of the CMECS (FGCD, 2012) Biotic Component classification. The CMECS partitions have been redefined into broad biotic groups and taxonomic classes, which more accurately reflect the spatial resolution at which information in the Australian context is available. These hierarchical Seamap divisions encompass 'presence', 'class', 'subclass', 'group', 'CATAMI morphospecies' and 'species'.  The new divisions are based loosely on phylogenetic groups, with the broadest grouping in the higher levels. By using broad phylogenetic groups any dependency on substratum type (as is the case in CMECS) is removed and a true hierarchical structure is enforced. Seamap also introduces concepts for bare and unmapped areas, both of which can have important ecological ramifications. The CATAMI classification  (CATAMI Technical Working Group, 2013) is the 5th level of the Seamap scheme. Once biota have been identified to the finest level of the CATAMI scheme, species identifications are added where available.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A hard substratum composed of a mix of Consolidated Hard Substrata and Unconsolidated Hard Substrata where neither class is dominant (i.e. does not exceed ≥ 80 %) of the substratum surface/composition.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An area where mapping has occurred, however the presence or absence of biota was not assessed. An NA classification is distinct from an Unknown classification in that an Unknown implies an assessment was made however a classification was not possible for any reason (e.g. inadequate resolution).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Areas where benthic biota are present in the observational unit and account for a total ≥ 5 % of the substratum surface/composition/biomass.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A habitat where the dominant biota are plants or algae.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A habitat dominated by benthic macrofauna that do not have a backbone, i.e. are not vertebrates.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Areas dominated by microbes that form a soft or hard structure visible to the eye. Soft structures are usually formed through accumulations of conspecifics and other microbes into a matrix that appears as strands, a thin film, or a thicker mat. Hard structures generally form through secretions and entrapment of minerals and sediments.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: This term describes vegetation that exists exclusively in areas that are permanently water logged, but may only be inundated with saline or brackish water periodically or occasionally. This includes areas such as marshes, tidal flats and river estuaries, but excludes oceans.  At the Highest Astronomical Tide (HAT) mark, vegetation in this class is never fully submerged and typically only the roots are immersed.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: This term describes vegetation that exists in areas that are inundated either permanently or with regular tidal flow. At the Highest Astronomical Tide (HAT) mark, this vegetation is fully submerged.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A filter feeder habitat is characterised by biota dominated by organisms that feed by drawing water through a specialised structure and filtering out small particles and organisms in the water column.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Bioturbation refers to the signs and traces formed by the activity of macrofauna living in soft sediment habitats. This can include evidence of burrows, feeding or crawling traces and mounds from a hugely diverse group of organisms. While direct observations of the fauna may not be common, the existence of these traces and the type of trace can help inform which types of bioturbators might be present in an area.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A hard substratum where the dominant grainsize is ≥ 256 mm in any dimension.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Biota with a shell.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An area dominated by mangroves, a tree or shrub that occurs in saline and brackish water in coastal and estuarine environments between low and high tide levels on sheltered shores. Mangroves are typically considered a tropical species, however in Australia some species occur in temperate regions as well. They typically have a tangled, above ground root system, and can form extensive swampy forests (as in Edgar 2008).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An area dominated by saltmarsh plants (halophytes). These typically occur on sheltered intertidal mud and sand flats. They are easily distinguished from other plants in that their roots are (semi-) regularly inundated by saltwater, and from mangroves based on their smaller size (as in Edgar, 2008).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An area dominated by macroalgae, i.e. multicellular algae that are capable of attaching to the seafloor (CATAMI 2014). Macroalgae are commonly referred to as seaweeds, and consist of the phyla Chlorophyta and Rhodophyta, and class Phaeophyceae.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Areas dominated by seagrass, a flowering plant (angiosperm; Phylum Magnoliophyta) that typically occurs in sheltered intertidal or subtidal environments, and has elongated green and grass-like leaves.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A hard substratum where grain sizes of < 256 mm in any dimension are dominant (i.e ≥ 80 % of the hard substratum surface)

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: A colonial animal of the Phylum Bryozoa that consist of numerous zooids, small box-like units about 1 mm long. They generally have a chitinous or calcareous covering that adds structural support, and feed by extending tentacles from an orifice in the upper sidewall. They may occur in many growth forms, including as flat encrusting, branched, fenestrate, soft dendroid and fouling communities (as in Edgar 2008, FGDC 2012).

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An area dominated by sponges, simple multicellular animals of the Phylum Porifera that live attached to the seafloor. Their soft and porus body structure is supported by a framework of fibrous proteins, and spicules of calcium carbonate or silica. Sponges are morphologically diverse, but all draw in a current of water using specialised flagella and extract nutrients and oxygen from the flow.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An area dominated by ascidians (also known as seasquirts or tunicates; Class Ascidiacea), a diverse group of solitary or colonial animals, the adults of which are sessile. Ascidians are bag-like filter feeders, drawing water in and out through separate inhalant and exhalent siphons.  They occur from intertidal to deep ( > 2000 m) subtidal waters, and can reach high abundances.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: Areas dominated by anemones, hydroids, hydrocorals or other benthic Cnidaria that are not corals.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An area dominated by accumulations of living oysters attached to a substratum.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An area dominated by accumulations of living mussels attached to a substratum.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/publishe.value: Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies (IMAS) - UTAS

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/source.value: SeaMap Australia National Benthic Habitat Classification Scheme (2017)

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: An areas dominated by accumulations of living shells other that oysters, mussels, clams of screwshells, that are attached or closely associated with the substratum.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: The Biogeographic Setting consists of a three tiered hierarchy that partitions the environment into Realms, Provinces and Ecoregions - based on the Marine Ecoregions of the World (MEOW; Spalding et al. , 2007) and additionally uses the Integrated Marine and Coastal Regionalisation of Australia (IMCRA, 2006). IMCRA (2006) consists of two levels, provinces which align approximately with MEOW Ecoregion boundaries and bioregions which nest under IMCRA provinces.These bioregions have been widely adopted for marine conservation and management purposes across Australia and as such are a useful addition to the biogeographic hierarchy.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.value: The Aquatic Setting in the CMECS (FGDC, 2012) Standard comprises three hierarchical levels (System, Subsystem and Tidal Zone) separating ocean, estuarine and lacustrine environments, deep and shallow waters, and submerged and intertidal environments. The 'system' is based on salinity and geomorphological characteristics, the 'subsystem' separates classes according to depth and position relative to the shoreline, and 'tidal zone' is determined by tidal influence. This Seamap classification setting has, however, been modified from CMECS in that the boundary between Open Water and Coastal Estuarine subsystems from 4m to 6m now align with the RAMSAR Wetlands of International Importance (UNESCO 1971) as suggested by Edmunds and Flynn (2015). Additionally the CMEC Standard Aquatic Setting uses Mean Lower Low Water (MLLW) and Mean Higher High Water (MHHW), to define tidal zones and estuarine subsystems, but Seamap considers the Lowest Astronomical Tide (LAT) and Highest Astronomical Tide (HAT) to be a better representation of these zones. The Seamap Aquatic Settings classification only applies to benthic substrates on the continental shelf between the HAT and 200m depth contour and Aquatic Setting concept definitions are modified to reflect this where necessary. CMECS Aquatic Setting classes outside of this zone (Marine oceanic, supra tidal zones) are excluded.
